<heading bold="true" box="[151,497,513,539]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,497,513,539]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" box="[151,304,513,539]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
vs 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[345,497,513,539]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,585,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">
Due to uncertain stratigraphic occurrences it is difficult to determine the age of the earliest definite cheiruroidean trilobites. The genera 
<taxonomicName authority="Rozova, 1960" authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[398,703,621,647]" class="Trilobita" family="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" genus="Eocheirurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[398,536,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Eocheirurus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rozova, A. V." box="[544,703,621,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref17043" refString="Rozova, A. V. (1960) [Upper Cambrian trilobites from Salair (Tolsochikninsk Suite)]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 5, 1 - 116. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1960">Rozova, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Rozova, 1960" authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[763,1039,621,647]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Emsurina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[763,872,622,647]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Emsurina</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rozova, A. V." box="[880,1039,621,647]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref17043" refString="Rozova, A. V. (1960) [Upper Cambrian trilobites from Salair (Tolsochikninsk Suite)]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 5, 1 - 116. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1960">Rozova, 1960</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, were proposed as cheirurids. Each contains obviously cheiruroidean species from the Tolstochi’kha Formation of Salair Ridge in the Altai-Sayan fold belt of southwestern Siberia. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozova, A. V." box="[483,651,693,720]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref17043" refString="Rozova, A. V. (1960) [Upper Cambrian trilobites from Salair (Tolsochikninsk Suite)]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 5, 1 - 116. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1960">Rozova (1960)</bibRefCitation>
also proposed the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[940,1054,693,719]" class="Trilobita" family="Corynexochida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Emsurella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Corynexochida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[940,1054,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Emsurella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and considered it a cheirurid, but subsequent authors (
<bibRefCitation author="Westrop, S. R." box="[384,553,729,755]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 179" refId="ref17352" refString="Westrop, S. R. (1986) Trilobites of the Upper Cambrian Sunwaptan Stage, southern Canadian Rocky Mountains, Alberta. Palaeontographica Canadiana, 3, 1 - 179." type="journal article" year="1986">Westrop, 1986</bibRefCitation>
, p. 68; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jell, P. A. &amp; Adrain, J. M." box="[642,890,729,755]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="331 - 553" refId="ref15817" refString="Jell, P. A. &amp; Adrain, J. M. (2003) Available generic names for trilobites. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 48, 331 - 553." type="journal article" year="2003">Jell and Adrain, 2003</bibRefCitation>
, p. 371) have suggested it belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Shaw, 1956" authorityName="Shaw" authorityYear="1956" class="Trilobita" family="Cheilocephalidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Cheilocephalidae 
<bibRefCitation author="Shaw, A. B." box="[253,386,764,791]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="48 - 52" refId="ref17189" refString="Shaw, A. B. (1956) A Cambrian Aphelaspis fauna from Steel Butte, near Boulder, Wyoming. Journal of Paleontology, 30, 48 - 52." type="journal article" year="1956">Shaw, 1956</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It is known from two species each represented only by cranidia. These are apparently proparian and with cheiruroidean dimensions, but seem to lack glabellar furrows. The similarly aged Siberian species 
<taxonomicName authority="(Maksimova, 1955)" authorityName="Maksimova" authorityYear="1955" baseAuthorityName="Maksimova" baseAuthorityYear="1955" box="[151,635,836,863]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Parapliomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="njuensis">
<emphasis box="[151,407,837,863]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Parapliomera njuensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Maksimova, Z. A." box="[421,627,836,863]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="117 - 135" refId="ref16068" refString="Maksimova, Z. A. (1955) [Class Trilobita]. In: Nikiforova, O. I. (Ed.), [Field atlas of the Ordovician and Silurian faunas of the Siberian Platform]. VESGEI, Gosgeoltekhizdat, Moscow, pp. 117 - 135. [in Russian]" type="book chapter" year="1955">Maksimova, 1955</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, however, has an assigned cranidium (
<bibRefCitation author="Maksimova, Z. A." box="[1062,1269,837,863]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 215" refId="ref16126" refString="Maksimova, Z. A. (1962) Trilobity ordovika i silura sibirskoj platformy [Ordovician and Silurian trilobites of the Siberian Platform]. Trudy Vsesoyuznogo Nauchno-Issledovatel'skogo Geologicheskogo Instituta (VSEGEI), New Series, 76, 1 - 215. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1962">Maksimova, 1962</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 17, fig. 13; see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Timohin, A. V." box="[247,416,873,899]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="82 - 91" refId="ref17283" refString="Timohin, A. V. (1989) Nizhneordovikskie trilobity [Lower Ordovician trilobites]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 1989, 82 - 91. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1989">Timohin, 1989</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 9, figs 8, 10, 14) that also has effaced furrows and the pygidia of this species certainly resemble those of pliomerids. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lane, P. D." box="[490,627,909,935]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref15979" refString="Lane, P. D. (1971) British Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 530, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1971">Lane (1971)</bibRefCitation>
assigned all three genera to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sdzuy" authorityYear="1955" box="[947,1062,909,935]" class="Trilobita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pilekiinae">Pilekiinae</taxonomicName>
, though he queried the affinity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[151,265,945,971]" class="Trilobita" family="Corynexochida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Emsurella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Corynexochida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Emsurella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozova, A. V." box="[279,445,945,972]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref17043" refString="Rozova, A. V. (1960) [Upper Cambrian trilobites from Salair (Tolsochikninsk Suite)]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 5, 1 - 116. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1960">Rozova (1960)</bibRefCitation>
considered all of the species she described to be late Cambrian in age. This was accepted by Přibyl and Vaněk (in 
<bibRefCitation author="Pribyl, A. &amp; Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I." box="[432,641,980,1007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="107 - 193" refId="ref16762" refString="Pribyl, A., Vanek, J. &amp; Pek, I. (1985) Phylogeny and taxonomy of family Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Acta Universitatis Palackianae Olomucensis Facultas rerum naturalium, 83, 107 - 193." type="journal article" year="1985">
Přibyl 
<emphasis box="[509,560,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
., 1985
</bibRefCitation>
), who considered 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[850,988,981,1007]" class="Trilobita" family="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" genus="Eocheirurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[850,988,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Eocheirurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be a pilekiine cheirurid, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[1306,1415,982,1007]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Emsurina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1306,1415,982,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Emsurina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a sphaerexochine cheirurid, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rozova" authorityYear="1960" box="[498,612,1017,1043]" class="Trilobita" family="Corynexochida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Emsurella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Corynexochida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[498,612,1017,1043]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Emsurella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a pliomerid. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lane, P. D." box="[765,896,1017,1043]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref15979" refString="Lane, P. D. (1971) British Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 530, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1971">Lane (1971</bibRefCitation>
, p. 73) suggested the age of these genera might be Tremadocian and 
<bibRefCitation author="Edgecombe, G. D." box="[386,594,1053,1079]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="144 - 177" refId="ref15295" refString="Edgecombe, G. D. (1992) Trilobite phylogeny and the Cambrian-Ordovician &quot; event: Cladistic reappraisal. In: Novacek, M. J. &amp; Wheel- er, Q. D. (Eds.), Extinction and Phylogeny. Columbia University Press, New York, pp. 144 - 177." type="book chapter" year="1992">Edgecombe (1992</bibRefCitation>
, p. 168–169) considered a Late Cambrian age suspect. It is now clear from conodont work that the Tolstochi’kha Formation spans the Cambrian–Ordovician boundary (
<bibRefCitation author="Sennikov, N. V. &amp; Tolmacheva, T. Yu. &amp; Obut, O. T. &amp; Izokh, N. G. &amp; Lykova, E. V." box="[1189,1432,1088,1115]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="594 - 610" refId="ref17114" refString="Sennikov, N. V., Tolmacheva, T. Yu., Obut, O. T., Izokh, N. G. &amp; Lykova, E. V. (2015) Zonation of the Siberian Ordovician deposits based on pelagic groups of fauna. Russian Geology and Geophysics, 56, 594 - 610. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. rgg. 2015.03.010" type="journal article" year="2015">
Sennikov 
<emphasis box="[1303,1352,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
, p. 606), with its upper part including assemblages assignable to the early Tremadocian 
<taxonomicName authority="Zone" authorityName="Zone" class="Conodonta" family="Conodonta (awaiting allocation)" genus="Iapetognathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Conodontophorida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fluctivagus">
<emphasis box="[1145,1436,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Iapetognathus fluctivagus</emphasis>
Zone
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zone" authorityName="Zone" box="[265,579,1161,1187]" class="Conodonta" family="Proconodontidae" genus="Cordylodus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Proconodontida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="angulatus">
<emphasis box="[265,513,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Cordylodus angulatus</emphasis>
Zone
</taxonomicName>
(see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Petrunina, Z. E. &amp; Izokh, N. G. &amp; Sennikov, N. V. &amp; Gabova, M. F." box="[693,940,1161,1187]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="209 - 211" refId="ref16658" refString="Petrunina, Z. E., Izokh, N. G., Sennikov, N. V. &amp; Gabova, M. F. (2001) Co-occurrences of trilobites, graptolites and conodonts from upper part of the Tolstochikha Formation (Tremadocian of Salair). In: Podobina, V. M. (Ed.), Evolution of Life on the Earth: Proceedings of the II International Symposium &quot; Evolution of Life on the Earth &quot;, Tomsk, 12 - 15 November. NTL, Tomsk, 209 - 211. [in Russian]" type="book chapter" year="2001">
Petrunina 
<emphasis box="[808,858,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
., 2001
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Rozova, A. V." box="[961,1129,1161,1188]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 116" refId="ref17043" refString="Rozova, A. V. (1960) [Upper Cambrian trilobites from Salair (Tolsochikninsk Suite)]. Trudy Instituta Geologii i Geofiziki. Sibirskoe Otdelenie, Akademiya Nauk SSSR, 5, 1 - 116. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1960">Rozova (1960)</bibRefCitation>
gave the provenance of all of the relevant species as the upper horizon of the formation. Hence the age remains equivocal and could be Late Cambrian, but is possible that they are all from the Ordovician (early Tremadocian).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="202" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,585,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">
“ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Reed" authorityYear="1896" box="[212,364,1269,1295]" class="Trilobita" family="Phacopida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Anacheirurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[212,364,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Anacheirurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
? sp.” of Apollonov and Čugaeva (in 
<bibRefCitation author="Apollonov, M. K. &amp; Cugaeva, M. N. &amp; Duninina, S. V." box="[772,1025,1269,1295]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" refId="ref14829" refString="Apollonov, M. K., Cugaeva, M. N. &amp; Duninina, S. V. (1984) [Trilobites and conodonts from the Batyrbay Section (Uppermost Cambrian-Lower Ordovician) in Malyi Karatau Range (atlas of the palaeontological plates)]. &quot; Nauka Kazakh SSR Publishing House, Alma-Ata, 48 pp." type="book" year="1984">
Apollonov 
<emphasis box="[898,946,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
., 1984
</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 22, figs 5–7) was based on specimens derived from a horizon at 
<quantity box="[503,573,1305,1331]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1399999999999997" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" unit="m" value="214.0">214 m</quantity>
in the Batyrbai Section, Malyi Karatau Range, southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1200,1334,1305,1331]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
. This horizon lies within the 
<taxonomicName box="[378,575,1341,1367]" class="Conodonta" family="Proconodontidae" genus="Cordylodus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Proconodontida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="prion">
<emphasis box="[378,575,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Cordylodus prion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
assemblage of 
<bibRefCitation author="Apollonov, M. K. &amp; Cugaeva, M. N. &amp; Dubinina, S. V." box="[744,999,1341,1367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="15 - 17" refId="ref14779" refString="Apollonov, M. K., Cugaeva, M. N. &amp; Dubinina, S. V. (1981) The Cambrian-Ordovician boundary in the Malyi Karatau Range, south Kazakhstan. United States Geological Survey Open-File Report, 81 - 743, 15 - 17." type="journal article" year="1981">
Apollonov 
<emphasis box="[870,919,1341,1367]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
. (1981
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 1), which correlates with the latest Cambrian 
<taxonomicName authority="Zone. Hence" authorityName="Zone. Hence" box="[268,670,1377,1403]" class="Conodonta" family="Proconodontidae" genus="Cordylodus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Proconodontida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lindstromi">
<emphasis box="[268,519,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Cordylodus lindströmi</emphasis>
Zone. Hence
</taxonomicName>
, this species, known from only three incomplete cranidia, but clearly cheiruroidean, may represent the oldest known, apparently latest Cambrian, cheiruroidean taxon. Other cheirurid genera with putative early Tremadocian species include 
<taxonomicName authority="Lu and Sun in Zhou et al. (1977)" authorityName="Lu and Sun in Zhou" authorityYear="1977" box="[786,1291,1449,1475]" class="Trilobita" family="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" genus="Chashania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[786,907,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Chashania</emphasis>
Lu and Sun in 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhou, T. - M. &amp; Liu, Y. - R. &amp; Meng, X. - S. &amp; Sun, Z. - H." box="[1083,1291,1449,1475]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="104 - 266" refId="ref17605" refString="Zhou, T. - M., Liu, Y. - R., Meng, X. - S. &amp; Sun, Z. - H. (1977) [Trilobita]. In: [Palaeontological Atlas of Central and South China. I. Early Palaeozoic]. Geological Publishing House, Beijing, pp. 104 - 266. [in Chinese]" type="book chapter" year="1977">
Zhou 
<emphasis box="[1150,1200,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">et al</emphasis>
. (1977)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kobayashi, 1934" authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1934" class="Trilobita" family="Pilekiidae" genus="Parapilekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1436,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Parapilekia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[151,343,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="521 - 585" refId="ref15885" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1934) The Cambro-Ordovician formations and faunas of South Chosen. Palaeontology. Part II. Lower Ordovician faunas. Journal of the Faculty of Science, Imperial University of Tokyo, Section 2, 3, 521 - 585." type="journal article" year="1934">Kobayashi, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lu and Qian in Yin and Li, 1978" authorityName="Lu and Qian in Yin and Li" authorityYear="1978" box="[352,900,1485,1511]" class="Trilobita" family="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" genus="Pseudopliomera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trilobita (awaiting allocation)" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,536,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Pseudopliomera</emphasis>
Lu and Qian in 
<bibRefCitation author="Yin, G. - Z. &amp; Li, S. - J." box="[711,900,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="385 - 595" refId="ref17550" refString="Yin, G. - Z. &amp; Li, S. - J. (1978) [Trilobita]. In: [Palaeontological Atlas of Southwest China. Guizhou Province. I. Cambrian-Devonian]. Geological Publishing House, Beijing, pp. 385 - 595. [in Chinese]" type="book chapter" year="1978">Yin and Li, 1978</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kobayashi, 1934" authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1934" box="[910,1202,1485,1511]" class="Trilobita" family="Phacopida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Seisonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[910,1005,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Seisonia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[1010,1202,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="521 - 585" refId="ref15885" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1934) The Cambro-Ordovician formations and faunas of South Chosen. Palaeontology. Part II. Lower Ordovician faunas. Journal of the Faculty of Science, Imperial University of Tokyo, Section 2, 3, 521 - 585." type="journal article" year="1934">Kobayashi, 1934</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Peng, 1990" authorityName="Peng" authorityYear="1990" class="Trilobita" family="Phacopida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Sinoparapilekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1257,1436,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Sinoparapilekia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Peng, S. - C." box="[151,282,1521,1547]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="55 - 171" refId="ref16559" refString="Peng, S. - C. (1990) Tremadoc stratigraphy and trilobite faunas of northwestern Hunan. 2. Trilobites from the Panjiazui Formation and the Madaoyu Formation in Jiangnan Slope Belt. Beringeria, 2, 55 - 171." type="journal article" year="1990">Peng, 1990</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It seems that cheiruroideans appeared in Siberia, North and South 
<collectingCountry box="[1050,1120,1521,1547]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">China</collectingCountry>
, and other tropical terranes, around the time of the Cambrian–Ordovician transition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,585,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">
No cheiruroideans are known from Laurentia prior to the beginning of the Stairsian Stage in the upper Tremadocian. 
<taxonomicName authority="Demeter, 1973" authorityName="Demeter" authorityYear="1973" box="[211,605,1629,1655]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Rossaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pliomeris">
<emphasis box="[211,433,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Rossaspis pliomeris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Demeter, E. J." box="[438,605,1629,1655]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="37 - 65" refId="ref15266" refString="Demeter, E. J. (1973) Lower Ordovician pliomerid trilobites from western Utah. Brigham Young University Geology Studies, 20, 37 - 65." type="journal article" year="1973">Demeter, 1973</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, is the oldest known Laurentian species, occurring only a few metres above the Skullrockian–Stairsian boundary. 
<taxonomicName authority="Harrington, 1957" authorityName="Harrington" authorityYear="1957" box="[581,901,1664,1691]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Rossaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[581,691,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Rossaspis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Harrington, H. J." box="[702,901,1664,1691]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="811 - 812" refId="ref15531" refString="Harrington, H. J. (1957) Notes on new genera of Pliomeridae (Trilobita). Journal of Paleontology, 31, 811 - 812." type="journal article" year="1957">Harrington, 1957</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, will be revised with several new species in a forthcoming work. It appears to be a pliomerid. The northern Laurentian Stairsian contains both early pliomerids and considerable numbers of pilekiine cheirurids, including species belonging to 
<taxonomicName authority="Barton, 1915" authorityName="Barton" authorityYear="1915" box="[1062,1298,1736,1763]" class="Trilobita" family="Pilekiidae" genus="Pilekia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1062,1141,1737,1763]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Pilekia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Barton, D. C." box="[1149,1298,1736,1763]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="102 - 152" refId="ref14890" refString="Barton, D. C. (1915) A revision of the Cheirurinae, with notes on their evolution. Washington University Studies, 3, 102 - 152." type="journal article" year="1915">Barton, 1915</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and several new genera, all currently under study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="203" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,585,2015]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,863]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="203" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">
Among all of these early cheiruroideans there has been considerable confusion over which taxa belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
versus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[318,456,1845,1871]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
, and what potential synapomorphies characterize each clade. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1951" box="[1152,1302,1845,1871]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Tesselacauda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1152,1302,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Tesselacauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is emblematic of this, as it has been assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[575,710,1881,1907]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
by many authors (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Ross, R. J., Jr." box="[975,1100,1880,1907]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref16929" refString="Ross, R. J., Jr. (1951) Stratigraphy of the Garden City Formation in northeastern Utah, and its trilobite faunas. Peabody Museum of Natural History, Yale University, Bulletin, 6, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1951">Ross, 1951</bibRefCitation>
[Ross made no formal family assignments in his monograph, but he considered {
<bibRefCitation author="Ross, R. J., Jr." box="[726,859,1916,1943]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref16929" refString="Ross, R. J., Jr. (1951) Stratigraphy of the Garden City Formation in northeastern Utah, and its trilobite faunas. Peabody Museum of Natural History, Yale University, Bulletin, 6, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1951">Ross, 1951</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 2} 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1951" box="[954,1104,1917,1943]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Tesselacauda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[954,1104,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Tesselacauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be part of an evolutionary trend with the pliomerids 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Harrington" authorityYear="1957" box="[443,553,1954,1979]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Rossaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[443,553,1954,1979]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Rossaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Harrington, 1957" authorityName="Harrington" authorityYear="1957" box="[568,867,1952,1979]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Hintzeia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,663,1954,1979]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Hintzeia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Harrington, H. J." box="[671,867,1952,1979]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="811 - 812" refId="ref15531" refString="Harrington, H. J. (1957) Notes on new genera of Pliomeridae (Trilobita). Journal of Paleontology, 31, 811 - 812." type="journal article" year="1957">Harrington, 1957</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ross, 1951" authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1951" box="[927,1218,1952,1979]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Pseudocybele" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[927,1081,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="202">Pseudocybele</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ross, R. J., Jr." box="[1088,1218,1952,1979]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 161" refId="ref16929" refString="Ross, R. J., Jr. (1951) Stratigraphy of the Garden City Formation in northeastern Utah, and its trilobite faunas. Peabody Museum of Natural History, Yale University, Bulletin, 6, 1 - 161." type="journal article" year="1951">Ross, 1951</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
]; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, T." box="[1238,1431,1952,1979]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="355 - 493" refId="ref15931" refString="Kobayashi, T. (1955) The Ordovician fossils of the McKay Group in British Columbia western Canada, with a note on the early Ordovician palaeogeography. Journal of the Faculty of Science, Tokyo University, Section 2, 9, 355 - 493." type="journal article" year="1955">Kobayashi, 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Maksimova, Z. A." box="[151,357,1989,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="1 - 215" refId="ref16126" refString="Maksimova, Z. A. (1962) Trilobity ordovika i silura sibirskoj platformy [Ordovician and Silurian trilobites of the Siberian Platform]. Trudy Vsesoyuznogo Nauchno-Issledovatel'skogo Geologicheskogo Instituta (VSEGEI), New Series, 76, 1 - 215. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1962">Maksimova, 1962</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Demeter, E. J." box="[370,539,1989,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="37 - 65" refId="ref15266" refString="Demeter, E. J. (1973) Lower Ordovician pliomerid trilobites from western Utah. Brigham Young University Geology Studies, 20, 37 - 65." type="journal article" year="1973">Demeter, 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jell, P. A. &amp; Adrain, J. M." box="[552,796,1989,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="331 - 553" refId="ref15817" refString="Jell, P. A. &amp; Adrain, J. M. (2003) Available generic names for trilobites. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 48, 331 - 553." type="journal article" year="2003">Jell and Adrain, 2003</bibRefCitation>
) and to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hawle and Corda" authorityYear="1847" box="[890,1022,1989,2015]" class="Trilobita" family="Cheiruridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cheiruridae</taxonomicName>
by others (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Cernyseva, N. E." box="[1207,1396,1988,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="202" pagination="17 - 194" refId="ref15017" refString="Cernyseva, N. E. (1960) [Trilobita]. In: Orlov,. A. (Ed.), Osnovy paleontologii; spravocnik dla paleontologov i geologov SSSR. 8, Clenistonogie, trilobitoobraznye i rakoobraznye. Akademi Nauk SSSR, Moscow, pp. 17 - 194. [in Russian]" type="book chapter" year="1960">Černyševa, 1960</bibRefCitation>
[as “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sdzuy" baseAuthorityYear="1955" box="[161,284,152,179]" class="Trilobita" family="Pilekiidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pilekiidae</taxonomicName>
”]; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hupe, P." box="[314,450,152,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="111 - 345" refId="ref15747" refString="Hupe, P. (1955) Classification des Trilobites. Annales de Paleontologie, 41, 111 - 345." type="journal article" year="1955">Hupé, 1955</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lane, P. D." box="[464,595,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="1 - 95" refId="ref15979" refString="Lane, P. D. (1971) British Cheiruridae (Trilobita). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society, 530, 1 - 95." type="journal article" year="1971">Lane, 1971</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Dean, W. T." box="[609,743,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref15210" refString="Dean, W. T. (1989) Trilobites from the Survey Peak, Outram and Skoki formations (Upper Cambrian-Lower Ordovician) at Wilcox Pass, Jasper National Park, Alberta. Geological Survey of Canada Bulletin, 389, 1 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.4095 / 127615" type="journal article" year="1989">Dean, 1989</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lee, D. - C. &amp; Chatterton, B. D. E." box="[757,1051,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="683 - 702" refId="ref16006" refString="Lee, D. - C. &amp; Chatterton, B. D. E. (1997) Ontogenies of trilobites from the Lower Ordovician Garden City Formation of Idaho and their implications for the phylogeny of the Cheirurina. Journal of Paleontology, 71, 683 - 702. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000040142" type="journal article" year="1997">Lee and Chatterton, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Edgecombe, G. D. &amp; Chatterton, B. D. E. &amp; Waisfeld, B. G. &amp; Vaccari, N. E." box="[1065,1339,153,179]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="1144 - 1154" refId="ref15398" refString="Edgecombe, G. D., Chatterton, B. D. E., Waisfeld, B. G. &amp; Vaccari, N. E. (1999) Ordovician pliomerid and prosopiscid trilobites from Argentina. Journal of Paleontology, 73, 1144 - 1154. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0022336000031036" type="journal article" year="1999">
Edgecombe 
<emphasis box="[1206,1257,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al</emphasis>
., 1999
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Adrain, J. M." pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="297 - 336" refId="ref14342" refString="Adrain, J. M. (2013) A synopsis of Ordovician trilobite distribution and diversity. In: Harper, D. A. T. &amp; Servais, T. (Eds.), Early Palaeozoic Biogeography and Palaeogeography. Geological Society, London, Memoirs, 38, 297 - 336. https: // doi. org / 10.1144 / M 38.20" type="journal article" year="2013">Adrain, 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Adrain, J. M. &amp; Karim, T. S. &amp; Westrop, S. R. &amp; Landing, E." box="[220,436,189,215]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="167 - 214" refId="ref14639" refString="Adrain, J. M., Karim, T. S., Westrop, S. R. &amp; Landing, E. (2014) Trilobite biostratigraphy of the Stairsian Stage (upper Tremadocian) of the Ibexian Series, Lower Ordovician, western United States. Memoirs of the Association of Australasian Palaeontologists, 45, 167 - 214." type="journal article" year="2014">
Adrain 
<emphasis box="[305,354,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al</emphasis>
., 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Other early cheiruroidean genera have similar taxonomic histories.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<bibRefCitation author="Whittington, H. B." box="[199,413,225,251]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="911 - 922" refId="ref17433" refString="Whittington, H. B. (1961) Middle Ordovician Pliomeridae (Trilobita) from Nevada, New York, Quebec, Newfoundland. Journal of Paleontology, 35, 911 - 922." type="journal article" year="1961">Whittington (1961</bibRefCitation>
, p. 912–913) gave a diagnosis for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[824,959,225,251]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
and contrasted pliomerids with pilekiine cheirurids. He considered that pilekiines differed from pliomerids in that they have “the glabella parallel-sided or narrowing forward, eye lobe situated far forward, eye ridge running inward to the axial furrow, and pleural furrow situated medially.” In the current state of knowledge none of these features seem at all diagnostic, as each is found in both early cheirurids and pliomerids. Other early diagnoses of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[899,1034,369,395]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Holliday, S." box="[1108,1279,369,395]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="471 - 478" refId="ref15630" refString="Holliday, S. (1942) Ordovician trilobites from Nevada. Journal of Paleontology, 16, 471 - 478." type="journal article" year="1942">Holliday, 1942</bibRefCitation>
, p. 473) were similarly composed of general features shared with cheirurids, and there have been no synthetic modern treatments of the group. In order to justify a familial assignment of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1951" box="[790,940,441,467]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Tesselacauda" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[790,940,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Tesselacauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and in an attempt to better characterize the early morphologies of pliomerids and cheirurids, we discuss below what seem to be the most salient differences between them.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,152,863]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
In dorsal cephalic features, there are few differences between the groups. Floian pliomerids develop an adaxially curtailed fusion of the palpebral lobe and eye ridge which was termed a palpebro-ocular ridge by 
<bibRefCitation author="McAdams, N. E. B. &amp; Adrain, J. M." pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="491 - 540" refId="ref16174" refString="McAdams, N. E. B. &amp; Adrain, J. M. (2009) New pliomerid trilobite genus Lemureops from the Lower Ordovician (Ibexian; Tulean, Blackhillsian) of western Utah, USA. Memoirs of the Association of Australasian Palaeontologists, 37, 491 - 540." type="journal article" year="2009">McAdams and Adrain (2009)</bibRefCitation>
. In the genera 
<taxonomicName authority=", Panisaspis McAdams and Adrain, 2011 b" authorityName=", Panisaspis McAdams and Adrain" authorityYear="2011" box="[521,1088,621,647]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Hintzeia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[521,616,622,647]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Hintzeia</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[629,750,622,647]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Panisaspis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McAdams, N. E. B. &amp; Adrain, J. M." box="[757,1088,621,647]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="1 - 68" refId="ref16344" refString="McAdams, N. E. B. &amp; Adrain, J. M. (2011 b) Panisaspis, a new genus of pliomerid trilobites from the Lower Ordovician (Ibexian; Tulean and Blackhillsian) of the Great Basin, western USA. Zootaxa, 2969 (1), 1 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2969.1.1" type="journal article" year="2011">McAdams and Adrain, 2011b</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ross" authorityYear="1951" box="[1099,1253,621,647]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" genus="Pseudocybele" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1099,1253,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Pseudocybele</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and others, this feature, when not set in a crowded anterior position, is always separated from the axial furrow posteriorly by a pitted fixigenal field. However it is a feature that seems to have been developed at some point within the group, as it is absent from those Stairsian species we assign to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1913" box="[697,836,729,755]" class="Trilobita" family="Pliomeridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phacopida" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pliomeridae</taxonomicName>
. The only other strong contrast between the groups is that some cheirurids develop median occipital spines or glabellar spines, and these features are completely unknown in pliomerids. Cheirurids have a tendency to possess more prominent tuberculate sculpture, but there is considerable overlap in this feature. There are few other dorsal cephalic differences.
</paragraph>
